Single young specimen fruiting from heavily cubically rotted conifer wood(very degraded stump base).

results.notes: This polypore mushroom was found on October 18, 2023 on a dead beech tree alongside the cross country running trails here at the University of Maine. This mushroom has a dark brown, dry, smooth, and silky moderately indented pileus with a rolled margin. The stipe is hard, medium tan in coloration, smooth, and dry. There are no gills but rather pores. The pores are one layer and discolors (lighter tan to cream). This mushroom did not leave a spore print. The pileus is 4-8 cm in diameter. Grows in clusters/groups. The stipe is 2-3 cm in length. Does not bruise. Spores light colored almost transparent. Spores cylindrical 4-8 X 2-3 um

results.notes: This mushroom has a white, smooth, slippy, shiny, silky, and deeply indented pileus. The pileus ranges from 4-8cm. The pileus margin is rolled with even white gills that are decurrent. The gills 1-2mm apart and regular in shape. The stipe is white and identical in color to that of the pileus and gills. The stipe is hard, smooth, silky, dry, solid, and equal with no partial veil/ring. The base of the stipe is a mycelial pad. It grows alone and was found in a mixed forest pushing up through leaves and pine needles. It has a mild earthy smell. Slight blueish/greenish tinge on underside of pileus along gills. The stipe is about 2-4 cm in length depending on the maturity. Spore print white: Spores 7-9(um) by 8-11(um).

results.notes:
Fruiting amidst woody debris beneath Douglas fir and Western red cedar.
Cap: heavily wrinkled/lumpy(yet smooth).
Younger specimens with pale margin band(superficial due to heavy rain saturation).
Most specimens with cherry red/maroon cast.
Non staining where handled.
Harvested a single specimen.
Microscopy:
Mounted a small section of cap cuticle tissue in KOH.
Pileipellis: cylindrical to slightly enlarged at tips. Terminal cells equal to or slightly fatter/clavate than lower cells(confirming X. atropurpureus). Xerocomellus zelleri has more elliptical/round Pileipellis with terminal cells that are awl shaped(many with a papillate like point at tip).
Bisected and thoroughly dehydrated specimen for herbarium collection/genetic record.
